task_description: Facing the building to your North (approx. 11°), estimate the height of the main building in front of you in meters. Answer with one number and a short rationale.

reason: The current pitch of 0° may not capture the full height of the building; looking up will reveal the roofline to measure from ground to peak.
To measure the full height, I need to see both the base and roof; rotating down will reveal the ground level for a complete vertical reference.
The current 60° downward pitch shows the ground but not the building's base; rotating up to 0° pitch will align the view with the building's base for height measurement.
To measure the full height, I need to see the building's base; rotating down 60° from the current upward pitch will align the view with the ground level for accurate height estimation.
The current 60° downward pitch shows the ground but not the building's base; rotating up 60° will align the view with the horizon to capture the building's base for height measurement.
The building's full height is visible between 0° (base) and 60° (roof) pitch; using trigonometry with an estimated 10m distance, height = 10 * tan(60°) ≈ 17.3m.
